For oddjob flight-test vibration analysis, `vibe_psd_100hz_summary.py` (in each dated
`oddjob_vibeAnalysis_*` dir) builds a per-log CSV of 100 Hz and sub-30 Hz PSD peaks for
`vehicle_angular_velocity` and `sensor_gyro_fifo`. It reuses the FFT/PSD verbatim from
`/home/choudhury/tools/dev/imu_vibe/analyze_imu_vibration.py` (`direct_fft`, `fifo_to_series`),
imported with `sys.path.insert`. FFT window = in-air segment (`vehicle_land_detected`).

Non-obvious facts:
- The gyro of interest is selected by **`device_id=6684714`** (a 2 kHz `sensor_gyro_fifo`), not by
  `multi_id` — though it happens to be `multi_id=1` in all OD1A0xx logs. Instances 0/2 are
  different chips (8 kHz/9 kHz) and read very differently at 100 Hz on some axes.
- `vehicle_angular_velocity` is single-instance (0) with no `device_id` — it's the fused
  controller signal. The gyro feeding it comes from `sensor_selection.gyro_device_id`, but that
  topic is logged in only ~2 of 9 logs and can differ from the FIFO device (e.g. OD1A079 used
  3670026 for the controller rate while the FIFO analysis uses 6684714).
- The dominant vibration line is actually at **~99.4–99.5 Hz**, not exactly 100 Hz. Use a
  max-in-band [98,101] Hz pick, not nearest-peak-to-100 (which locks onto a tiny bump at 100.03).
- PSD peak height scales with FFT window length for a stationary tone, so values are only
  comparable across logs at equal-ish window durations.
- Flight date comes from **`sensor_gps.time_utc_usec`** (first valid >0 sample, UTC) — file mtime
  is unreliable (just the copy date). `time_ref_utc=0` and there's no other wall-clock source.
  Some oddjob logs (e.g. OD1A067/068/070/079) have no `sensor_gps` topic at all, so they have no
  recoverable date — leave blank rather than invent one.
